  <h1>False Claims Act Qui Tam Suits</h1>
  <h2>What Is a Qui Tam Suit?</h2>
  <p>A qui tam suit is a private lawsuit filed by a relator (whistleblower) on behalf of the federal government against a party that has defrauded the government. The phrase "qui tam" comes from a Latin phrase meaning "who as well [as for the king] sues."</p>
  <h2>Filing Under Seal</h2>
  <p>FCA qui tam complaints are filed under seal in federal court, meaning they are not publicly disclosed while the government investigates (typically 60 days, often extended for years). The relator's identity is protected during this period.</p>
  <h2>Government Intervention</h2>
  <p>The Department of Justice reviews the complaint during the seal period. If the government intervenes (takes over the case), the relator receives 15%–25% of the recovery. If the government declines and the relator proceeds alone, the award is 25%–30%.</p>
  <h2>FCA Damages</h2>
  <p>The FCA imposes treble damages (3× the government's losses) plus civil penalties per false claim ($13,000–$26,000 per claim as of 2024, adjusted for inflation). Total recoveries in large cases can be enormous.</p>
  <h2>Common FCA Cases</h2>
  <p>Healthcare fraud (Medicare/Medicaid overbilling) accounts for the majority of FCA recoveries. Defense contractor fraud, grant fraud, and customs fraud are other major categories. The government has recovered over $75 billion under the FCA since 1986.</p>
</BaseLayout>
